  "suggestion": "[neuroscience+Bayesian-inference+information-theory+Karl-Friston-active-inference] Free Energy Minimization (Active Inference Engine) — a concrete implementation of the Precision-Weighted Prediction Error idea. Every human response is computed as: minimize F = KL[beliefs||priors] - E[log likelihood of observations]. The model maintains a beliefs object (expectations about self, world, others), computes surprise when stimulus violates expectations, weights the surprise by precision (how reliable is this signal?), then outputs behavior as the action that minimizes expected free energy. Emotions are the precision-weighted surprise signal itself: high-precision violation = fear/anger/joy; low-precision = mild affect. This unifies cognition, emotion, and motivation under one equation. Implementation: beliefs are encoded as weighted maps in the person struct; predict() computes delta between expected and observed, scales by personalRelevance × arousal as precision proxy, routes to behavior via surprise magnitude and valence. — Math: F = KL[q(s) || p(s)] - E_q[log p(o|s)]; behavior = argmin_a E_a[F]; emotion_intensity = precision × prediction_error; [dynamical-systems+topology+bifurcation-theory+epigenetics-landscape] Attractor Landscape Psychology — model the mind as a potential energy landscape (Waddington-style) with four deep basins: Safety, Threat, Connection, Meaning. Every situation computes a perturbation vector pushing the person's current state across this landscape. Emotional state = current basin + distance to basin floor. Behavior = gradient descent toward nearest attractor given the perturbation. Personality traits = basin depths (e.g., high neuroticism = shallow Safety basin, easily perturbed into Threat). Psychopathology = pathological attractors or missing basins. Transitions between states follow bifurcation logic: small perturbations → smooth change; large perturbations cross saddle points → sudden phase shifts (panic attacks, falling in love, epiphanies). This explains why emotional responses are nonlinear and history-dependent. — Math: dx/dt = -∇V(x) + perturbation(stimulus); V(x) = Σ basin_depth_i × (x - attractor_i)²; emotion = ||x - floor(current_basin)||; behavior = sign(-∇V); [information-theory+Kolmogorov-complexity+narrative-psychology+MDL] Narrative Causality Compression — humans generate behavior by constructing the minimum-length causal story that makes the situation intelligible, then acting to maintain or resolve that story. Based on MDL (minimum description length): the brain adopts the hypothesis H that minimizes L(H) + L(data|H). Root cause is always whichever causal agent produces the shortest story. This explains: anthropomorphism (agents compress better than physics), conspiracy thinking (one cause compresses many events), grief (narrative rupture — the story's protagonist is gone), and humor (two competing compressions suddenly collapse into one). The model encodes a tiny story-builder: extract agent, intention, obstacle, outcome from the situation; score by narrative compressibility; predict emotion as fit-quality and behavior as the action that advances the best story toward resolution. — Math: K(situation) = min program length that generates observed pattern; behavior = argmin L(story | situation); emotion_valence = d/dt[story_coherence]; surprise = K(stimulus | current_story)",
